spec/unit/provider/cinder_type/openstack.message:
Just FYI, it is/was already testing for both. The regex is a global substitution on input that looks like this;
{u'new_key_with': u'dashed-value'}

then you have a gsub(/u'(\w*)'/, '"\1"') on that as a whole, giving the error;

Could not prefetch cinder_type provider 'openstack': 751: unexpected token at '{"new_key_with": u'dashed-value'}'

The new_key_with underscores passes the regex, the dashed-value doesn't.

With the new regex we're not only allowing for _values_ with dashes and other characters, but also _keys_. (It just so happened that our issue was with us having a dash in the value section.)

And I think the regex you suggested casting a wider net was the right call. We're not inserting values, we're just using what's already there. I don't think we need to do any validation of data that's already been allowed in.
